    <thetext>Description of problem:
Using interval=0 in the connectivity section should disable connectivity checking. With NetworkManager 1.8.0-0.2.rc2 on Fedora 26 Alpha the NetworkManager process is using about 25% CPU time on my test system.

Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable):
NetworkManager-1.8.0-0.2.rc2.fc26.x86_64

How reproducible:
always

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create the file /etc/NetworkManager/conf.d/99-myconfig.conf with the following content:

[connectivity]
interval=0

[logging]
level=DEBUG

2. Restart the NetworkManager service:

systemctl restart NetworkManager.service

3.

Actual results:
NetworkManager process has high CPU usage and floods the system logfile with messages like this (actual hostname replaced by &lt;hostname&gt; placeholder):

Apr 27 16:31:10 &lt;hostname&gt; NetworkManager[2805]: &lt;debug&gt; [1493303470.8497] connectivity: (wlp2s0) faking request. Connectivity check disabled
Apr 27 16:31:10 &lt;hostname&gt; NetworkManager[2805]: &lt;debug&gt; [1493303470.8499] connectivity: (wlp2s0) faking request. Connectivity check disabled
Apr 27 16:31:10 &lt;hostname&gt; NetworkManager[2805]: &lt;debug&gt; [1493303470.8501] connectivity: (wlp2s0) faking request. Connectivity check disabled
Apr 27 16:31:10 &lt;hostname&gt; NetworkManager[2805]: &lt;debug&gt; [1493303470.8504] connectivity: (wlp2s0) faking request. Connectivity check disabled

Expected results:
NetworkManager does not check the internet connection.

Additional info:
The default interval on Fedora is 300 seconds, and this is configured in /usr/lib/NetworkManager/conf.d/20-connectivity-fedora.conf.</thetext>
